[div class=p 
	[a class=intlink href=/Users/Profile/feos 
		"feos
	]a
	": Indeed the previous movie didn't seem to care about the time score tally takes, and it takes an extra frame for every 20 points.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"If we take this movie's gameplay time from the encode (197.95 seconds) and adjust it from 69.3923791043Hz that PCem uses for DOS's 70Hz mode (25.175MHz clock) to 70.0863028953Hz that it's meant to be, we get 195.99 seconds, so 1.242 seconds of gameplay improvement over the old movie (which was 197.232 seconds long in gameplay). Now PCem st1 runs at 100fps at all times, but realtime duration is still more or less representative, aside from requiring 
	[a href=https://github.com/TASEmulators/pcem/issues/13 rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"a tiny speedup
	]a
	".
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Accepting as an improvement.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Note that firmware for PCem v17 for some reason has a different 
	[code 
		"pb570/gd5430.bin
	]code
	" file that doesn't sync with this movie. It requires v16's version of it, which is what our early90s setup also used.
	$LF
